{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518135","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518135"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:00:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12883"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12883"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.27,0.24,0.36]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5325"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53782"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5325","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5325"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12883"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39237"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"125"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2869"},{"type":"tags","id":"4978"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9051"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9085"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14095"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16119"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43363"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53782","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53782"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with worsening lower back pain. He was diagnosed with metastatic prostate cancer two months ago after presenting to his General Practitioner with worsening lower back pain, fatigue, and unintentional weight loss. The pain is now aching and persistent and has significantly worsened over the past few days. He has been taking regular over-the-counter paracetamol without effect. His medical history includes ischaemic heart disease and chronic hepatitis B virus infection. His regular medications are aspirin and entecavir.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with vital signs within normal limits. An MRI scan and a biopsy along with blood tests have confirmed the diagnosis of carcinoma of the prostate with bony metastases. A pathological fracture is seen in L3. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine clearance: 30 mL/min (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPSA: 142 ng/mL (4-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 89 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (140-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlbumin: 26 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has been started on degarelix/docetaxel and 8 Gy external beam radiation therapy. He requires analgesia for his pain.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate oral analgesia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Paracetamol","Celecoxib","Morphine","Tramadol","Hydromorphone"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate analgesia in this scenario would be \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydromorphone\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient has bony metastases from prostate cancer and a recent pathological fracture, which explains his acute on chronic back pain. In cancer pain, opioids are appropriate first-line treatment for severe pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has signs of chronic liver disease (as shown in reduced platelet count and albumin level most likely caused by his chronic HBV infection) as well as chronic kidney disease (creatinine clearance \u0026lt;60 mL/min). This would significantly affect drug choice.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydromorphone is an opioid that is approximately five times more potent than morphine. The major metabolite is hydromorphone-3-glucuronide which has no opioid activity. Accumulation of hydromorphone-3-glucuronide, can occur in patients with renal disease as it is renally excreted however, as it has no opioid activity, this makes it a preferred option in patients with renal impairment compared to the other options. Other opioids that may be suitable include buprenorphine, oxycodone, and fentanyl.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorphine\u003C/strong\u003E, like hydromorphone, is an opioid. It is metabolised to morphine-6-glucuronide, which is a more potent opioid than morphine, and morphine-3-glucuronide. As morphine-6-glucuronide can accumulate in patients with renal impairment this can result in opioid toxicity and as such, morphine is best avoided in patients with chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParacetamol\u003C/strong\u003E is a good analgesic and may be effective for less severe pain. This patient however has trialled paracetamol over-the-counter but found it ineffective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECelecoxib\u003C/strong\u003E is a COX-2 selective NSAID. It is most commonly used for its anti-inflammatory and analgesic properties. The use of celecoxib (and other NSAIDs) is best avoided if creatinine clearance is \u0026lt;30 mL/min. Furthermore, its use should be limited in patients who are on concomitant aspirin due to its likelihood of causing gastrointestinal side effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETramadol\u003C/strong\u003E is a drug that has a weak affinity for mu opioid receptor, but mainly acts as a norepinephrine and serotonin reuptake inhibitor. Most of the opioid analgesic activity of tramadol results from its metabolism to M1 by CYP2D6 liver enzymes. M1 is excreted renally and it is therefore not recommended in the setting of significant renal impairment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with significant renal impairment, morphine, tramadol and celecoxib are best avoided.","Hydromorphone, oxycodone, buprenorphine, and fentanyl are preferred over morphine and tramadol in patients with significant renal impairment.","Opioids are appropriate first-line treatment for severe cancer-related pain."],"references":["Schug SA, Palmer GM, Scott DA, Alcock M, Halliwell R, Mott JF; APM:SE Working Group of the Australian and New Zealand College of Anaesthetists and Faculty of Pain Medicine. 2020. Acute Pain Management: Scientific Evidence (5th edition), ANZCA \u0026 FPM, Melbourne. Available at: https://www.anzca.edu.au/resources/college-publications/acute-pain-management/apmse5.pdf","Australian Medicines Handbook. 2020. Available at: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/auth","Opioids in pain management. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [online]. 2020; accessed 2023 May. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39237"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12883"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39237"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-25T20:08:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-25T20:09:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5325"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53782"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"44","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/44"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude79","name":"Pain Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"112","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/112"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Prostate cancer","synonyms":["Prostate tumour","Prostate malignancy","Carcinoma of the prostate","Prostate adenocarcinoma","Metstatic prostate cancer"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T11:34:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/125"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Back pain","synonyms":["Lower back pain","Lumbar back pain","Chronic back pain"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:03+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-01T11:20:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"typ